Average Time Spent Buckets for Purchasers and Abandoners¶

In [15]:
pur_grp = pd.DataFrame(df_pur['avg_tm_bkt'].value_counts())
pur_grp = pur_grp.reset_index()
pur_grp.columns = ['Time_Bucket','Customers count']
pur_grp = pur_grp.sort_values(by='Time_Bucket', ascending=1)

aban_grp = pd.DataFrame(df_aban['avg_tm_bkt'].value_counts())
aban_grp = aban_grp.reset_index()
aban_grp.columns = ['Time_Bucket','Customers count']
aban_grp = aban_grp.sort_values(by='Time_Bucket', ascending=1)

# Creating trace1
trace1 = go.Scatter(
                    x = pur_grp.Time_Bucket,
                    y = pur_grp['Customers count'],
                    mode = "lines",
                    name = "Purchasers Behaviour",
                    marker = dict(color = 'rgba(16, 112, 2, 0.8)'))
# Creating trace2
trace2 = go.Scatter(
                    x = aban_grp.Time_Bucket,
                    y = aban_grp['Customers count'],
                    mode = "lines+markers",
                    name = "Abandoners Behaviour",
                    marker = dict(color = 'rgba(80, 26, 80, 0.8)'))
data = [trace1, trace2]
layout = dict(title = 'Average Time Spent Buckets for Purchasers and Abandoners',
              xaxis= dict(title= 'Purchasers VS Abandoners Time Spent',ticklen= 5,zeroline= False)
             )
fig = dict(data = data, layout = layout)
iplot(fig)

Note: We see that there are over 12,000 abandoners out of 29,189 who are exiting the application before 10 minutes.

In [16]:
# Outlier Removal:

def outlier_treatment(datacolumn):
 sorted(datacolumn)
 Q1,Q3 = np.percentile(datacolumn , [25,75])
 IQR = Q3 - Q1
 lower_range = Q1 - (1.5 * IQR)
 upper_range = Q3 + (1.5 * IQR)
 return lower_range,upper_range

print("Outlier boundaries for Monetary Value")
print(outlier_treatment(df_pur['shopping_spent_tm']))
print(outlier_treatment(df_pur['shopping_visits']))
print(outlier_treatment(df_aban['shopping_spent_tm']))
print(outlier_treatment(df_aban['shopping_visits']))

Avg Time Spent in Each path for Purchases and Abandoners:¶

In [21]:
merge = pd.concat([pur_top_paths, aban_top_paths])
merge = merge.reset_index()
def SetColor(x):
    if(x < 0.5):
        return "crimson"
    elif(x > 0.5):
        return "aquamarine"
purchase_ind = merge['purchase_ind']
trace1 = go.Scatter(
                        x = merge.spent_tm,
                        y = merge['Path Number'],
                        mode = "markers",
                        name = "Purchasers & Abandoners Time Spent in top paths",
                        marker = dict( color=list(map(SetColor, purchase_ind)),line=dict(width=2,color='DarkSlateGrey')),
                        text= merge.nav_path_sort)

layout = dict(title = 'Avg Time Spent in Each path for Purchases and Abandons',
                  xaxis= dict(title= 'Avg Time spent',ticklen= 5,zeroline= False))
data = [trace1]
fig = dict(data = data, layout = layout)
iplot(fig)

Note: It is observed that the average time spent leading to most of the purchases is around 40 to 45 minutes. There are comparitively less purchases if the Avg time is either too low or too high.

If Avg time spent is too low - Customer not interested in Purchasing
If Avg time spent is too high - Customer is not convinced of making the purchase. ie, he has second thoughts

In [25]:
#Function to Create a PieChart
def PieChart(column, title, limit):
    
    color = ['red',  'navy',  'cyan', 'lightgrey','orange', 'gold','lightgreen', 
                            '#D0F9B1','tomato', 'tan']

    trace1 = go.Pie(labels=pur_sum['Module'], 
                    values=pur_sum['Total_Time_Spent'], 
                    name= "Purchasers", 
                    hole= .5, 
                    domain= {'x': [0, .48]},
                   marker=dict(colors=color))

    trace2 = go.Pie(labels=aban_sum['Module'], 
                    values=aban_sum['Total_Time_Spent'], 
                    name="Abandoners", 
                    hole= .5,  
                    domain= {'x': [.52, 1]})

    layout = dict(title= title, font=dict(size=15), legend=dict(orientation="h"),
                  annotations = [
                      dict(
                          x=.20, y=.5,
                          text='Module', 
                          showarrow=False,
                          font=dict(size=20)
                      ),
                      dict(
                          x=.81, y=.5,
                          text='Module', 
                          showarrow=False,
                          font=dict(size=20)
                      )
        ])

    fig = dict(data=[trace1, trace2], layout=layout)
    py.iplot(fig)

K-Means Clustering for grouping the Target Market¶

In [35]:
abandoners = df_aban.groupby('cust_id').sum()

abandoners = abandoners[abandoners['spent_tm'] < 100]
abandoners = abandoners[abandoners['shopping_click_cnt'] < 100]

clstr = abandoners[['spent_tm','shopping_click_cnt']]
X=clstr.iloc[:].values

#applying K-means
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
kmeans=KMeans(n_clusters=4,init='k-means++',max_iter=300,n_init=10,random_state=0)
y_kmeans=kmeans.fit_predict(X)

trace0 = go.Scatter(
    x=X[y_kmeans==0,0],
    y=X[y_kmeans==0,1],
    name = 'Careless',
    mode='markers',
    marker=dict(size=11,
        color=('paleturquoise')
               )
)

trace1 = go.Scatter(
      x = X[y_kmeans==1,0],
    y = X[y_kmeans==1,1],
    name = 'Careful',
    mode='markers',
    marker=dict(size=11,
        color = ('aqua')
               )
)

trace2 = go.Scatter(
      x = X[y_kmeans==2,0],
    y = X[y_kmeans==2,1],
    name = 'Sensible',
    mode='markers',
    marker=dict(size=11,
        color = ('aquamarine')
               )
)

trace3 = go.Scatter(
      x = X[y_kmeans==3,0],
    y = X[y_kmeans==3,1],
    name = 'Target',
    mode='markers',
    marker=dict(size=11,
        color = ('darkturquoise')
               )
)

data = [trace0, trace1,trace2,trace3]
layout = dict(title = 'Cluster of Customers',
              xaxis = dict(title = 'Shopping Click Counts'),
              yaxis = dict(title = 'Total Spent Time')
             )

fig = dict(data=data, layout=layout)
fig['layout']['xaxis'].update(dict(title = 'Shopping Click Counts', 
                                   tickmode='linear',
                                   tickfont = dict(size = 10), tickangle = 90))
py.iplot(fig)

Note: We have grouped our customers based on their shopping click counts and time spent in the MyVZ app. We have thus obtained the target market.

K-Means clustering has clustered the abandoners as Careless, Careful, Sensible and Target customers.
Marketing Strategy: Customers grouped as "Target" can be provided with promotions/discounts to ensure that they make a purchase.
